<TITLE> Manila to re-word territory draft to woo back rebels </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MANILA, Jan 9 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The Philippine government will re-word its offer for an ancestral homeland for around 3 million Muslims in the south of the country to persuade rebels to resume stop-start peace talks that have dragged on for over a decade. Jesus Dureza, the presidential adviser on the peace process, said on Wednesday Manila was willing to compromise its requirement that Congress approve a deal on territory that would be a key step in ending a near 40-year conflict that has killed more than 120,000 people. The Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF), the country's largest Muslim rebel group, objected to this requirement last month, fearing it could shrink the amount of territory ceded to them. "We're re-drafting the agreement on ancestral domain hoping to convince them to go back to negotiations as soon as possible," Dureza told reporters. "The president is determined to conclude a peace agreement with the Muslim rebels at all cost." Dureza said the government would ask both houses of Congress to amend the constitution to offer Muslims a federal system of governance in the largely Catholic country. "We're not reneging on all our consensus points with the MILF, but the government is constrained by our constitution," he said, explaining why talks bogged down in Malaysia in December. The rebel's chief negotiator told Reuters that the MILF was waiting to see what the government offered. "We're not against the constitutional processes. We're not trying to prevent the government from carrying it out as long as it would not affect what had been agreed upon by two parties," Mohaqher Iqbal said in a telephone interview. Dureza said they would show the MILF the new draft as soon as the president and her cabinet approved it. President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo has said she wants to end the Muslim rebellion before she steps down in June 2010. But many analysts doubt her ability to do so given her widespread unpopularity and opposition from powerful political c